 their attitude was based on a clear theological position, or on issues of socialisation. The book will primarily interest students and lecturers of Jewish/Christian relations, the Middle Ages, Jews in the Medieval period, and inter-religious research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianity and other religionsxJudaismxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJewsxIdentity. 0aJewszEurope, NorthernxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJudaismxRelationsxChristianityxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aApostasy.  aConversion.  aJewish Identity.  aJudaism.  aMiddle ages.  aSelf-identification.1 aGoldin, Simha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526129345zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526129345zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526129345/original  a978-3-11-128357-9 Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA